</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8636CFFF8BFF87FF78FEB0B2DFFEEA" blockId="10.[138,907,274,371]" box="[138,251,347,371]" pageId="10" pageNumber="4039">
<emphasis id="B94DEADDFF8BFF87FF78FEB0B2DFFEEA" box="[138,251,347,371]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="4039">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8636CFFF8BFF87FF78FE67B18BFE5D" blockId="10.[138,1185,396,452]" pageId="10" pageNumber="4039">The name ‘‘phomyaaw’’ refers to the long bristles on the abdominal sternites 5 and 6 (in Thai ‘‘yaaw’’ means ‘‘long’’ and ‘‘phom’’ means ‘‘hairs or bristles’’).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8636CFFF8BFF87FF78FE16B2D7FD8C" blockId="10.[138,243,509,533]" box="[138,243,509,533]" pageId="10" pageNumber="4039">
<emphasis id="B94DEADDFF8BFF87FF78FE16B2D7FD8C" box="[138,243,509,533]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="4039">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8636CFFF8BFF87FF78FDC5B329FD3E" blockId="10.[138,1185,558,679]" pageId="10" pageNumber="4039">Mostly yellow (including legs) species; one pair of verticals; occiput narrowly densely greyish pollinose behind eyes, otherwise subshining; mesonotum wholly yellow, thoracic pleura partly brown; abdominal sternite 5 with two, sternite 6 with four very long bristles posteriorly.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8636CFFF8BFF87FF78FD0BB37CFD61" blockId="10.[138,344,736,760]" box="[138,344,736,760]" pageId="10" pageNumber="4039">
<emphasis id="B94DEADDFF8BFF87FF78FD0BB37CFD61" box="[138,344,736,760]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="4039">Material examined</emphasis>
</paragraph>
